Need for Speed: The Run takes place across the United States.
<0xE2><0x80><0xA2> Review
Originally, a carefree ride turns into a routine morning trip to a sleigh due to a series of unnecessary rare errors.
While the ambition has been largely fulfilled, it is not valid if no one has apparently wanted to do anything more.
A new song, titled The Run, was born before the release of the album.
He promised that in the summer of the Need for Speed racing series would once again move a bit in a new direction, and from playable demonstrations it appeared as a game that in the genre of action racing would not have to be just in numbers.
We were also curious as to how the inserted passages in which the main hero will get out of the car and run on his own.
As with the NFS series, however, many are a little different than we expected.
These are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole pulls down a few unnecessary mistakes that have been appearing in the series for more or less a few years.
So these are not actually mistakes, but rather an expression of some incomprehensible laziness of developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are introduced to the story, whose protagonist Jack has certain problems of a personal character and as a solution is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
Behind the wheel you will sit on the west coast of San Francisco and your task is to arrive first in New York.
The idea carries with it a number of interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then into more than fifty races.
As a result, each race goes on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don’t even have the feeling that the game is always the same.
In addition, some of the environments are very nice to look at, although the technical level of graphics corresponds to previous parts of the series.
So it's nothing mundane.
But driving across the desert, in the autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains seems visually very pleasant.
In addition, the races are occasionally infused with some atypical element.
In the desert, for example, you get stuck in a sandstorm, which greatly reduces visibility.
In contrast, in the mountains, you need to be careful not to be swept away by avalanches.
In addition, the individual races are placed quite well behind each other.
There are only a few types, but that is enough.
For a while, you try to advance the required number of opponents (in essence a classic race), then you again gain time (a classic fight with the feet) and then you have a duel with a single opponent waiting for you.
From time to time, the police will also be involved, which makes all your efforts even more uncomfortable.
The news is the passages outside the car.
It’s more of an interactive animation where Jack usually runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right moments.
It's not complicated.
Surprisingly, however, these passages are much less in the game than you would expect (specifically, maybe even just three).
As a result, however, this is in favor of the thing, because this element does not have a chance to become annoying and in the context of the above it ranks among the elements that enhance the game.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of previous parts.
This means that it is no longer a nuisance these days, but it cannot be said that it would be a lockdown.
If you’re looking for a realistic simulation, you’ll have to look elsewhere.
But the more action-packed racing here still fits the model quite well, even though we could find better ones in the competition.
Until then, everything is in perfect order.
Problems are beginning to emerge after a while.
Unlike the model of a car, the model is no longer a collision model.
We do not expect this type of game to count complex deformations and collisions, but if you have no idea how your car will be maintained, then probably not everything is completely okay.
Typically, during a narrow pass or passing of cars in normal traffic, sometimes you only slightly lick each other, but at other times in an almost identical situation, your car will end up in wild pirouettes.
Or even attack it right away.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn’t bother you at all, but it will reliably distract you.
Restarts are resolved in such a way that, if you break or travel far off the track, the game will throw you back to the last catch point on the track.
However, there are only five restarts available in each race.
When you exhaust them, you have to start the race all over again.
So it’s more of a help in case something doesn’t work out than you can rely on it explicitly.
But sometimes even restarts will not help, it will solve them when it is necessary to learn the particular part of the race to remember.
The big draw of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some curves need to be crossed in a specific way, otherwise you won’t fit into them.
At other times, you will find "civilian" cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
Angry, especially in situations where you see an opponent passing through between two opposing cars easily in front of you, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive or brake them.
It doesn’t matter when you get to them, because it’s “calculated” so that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
Competitors have another advantage.
During the entire duration of the game you will encounter several places where, again, no matter the time, the same opponent will always overtake you in the same place.
The most it hits at the end of the game on a long bridge, where you go in the opposite direction.
Your opponent must get there in front of you at all costs.
When driving in front of you, you get a worse view of the anti-driving cars, so you’ll be there a couple of times.
You can understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-intensive, but the execution is so obvious that it will reliably dislike you quickly.
And it’s a shame, because despite the simple driving model, playing is fun and places and so action-packed that sometimes you literally don’t want to watch what’s flying.
And basically it doesn’t matter if it’s a concept with fifty unique tracks, arranging the races so that boredom doesn’t have a chance, or anything else.
An unconventional idea is to replace cars during races.
You have to pay attention to gasoline pumps on the way, because that’s where you can change the car, although in the vast majority of cases you’ll have enough of what you have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Athletes are suitable for urban areas, strong U.S. highway boulders and exotic supersports for technical riding, for example, on rugged mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand as well as the challenge mode, which are races in individual locations that you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points in your profile, which is common for challenges and story.
In order to obtain a higher level of the driver, different objects are unlocked: starting with cars and ending with backgrounds for the profile.
At the same time, it is re-connected with the online Autolog feature, which among other things compares your results with other players and provides additional community features.
One of the other hard-to-understand pitfalls is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you get to the subway tunnel (budiz), where you get married in the dark after the tracks (budiz).
The tachometer gives you numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (behind) and in it comes a subway set from the back and uncompromisingly picks you up.
In the editorial board, we will have a discussion for a few more days about whether no one really thought about the game, or whether the authors really think we are such a big fool.
The technical side of the game is nothing extra, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in some cases even great.
It’s a pity that in some of the more intense moments, the shooting decreases, and in some cases, it’s quite tragic.
However, this is especially the case with a larger number of participants, when the smooth shooting would no longer apply to you.
The sound page is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to please the widest possible range of rather younger audiences, a soundtrack was created from the category "every dog is a different village", but it can be assumed that because of listening to music someone will probably not buy the game.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is so much disappointing.
If the game were to avoid completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best NFS work in the last few years.
This is how the game works unfinished.
Fun is definitely fine, but be prepared for mistakes that will be rubbed into your eyes by the power of airport spotlights.
