For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, it is a company perceived as very contemporary, and yet it has been a hundred years since its founding.
The foundation for this long term was laid by the company’s first head, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already broken the motto that many of the world’s problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" thus became the imprint around which the life of the future giant will unfold (and also the title of an internal magazine, which began to be published at IBM as early as 1935).
It was also the foundation of Watson’s carefully built corporate culture.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking is a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and thrived for a hundred years because it remained true to its core values and was not afraid to change everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform technology, business and society during our first century.
We hope that in the second century we will be able to achieve even more," said Samuel J. Palmisano, the current CEO of the company.
An elaborated system
In the 1930s, Watson took care of his employees just like the businessman of Bata in the Czech Republic - the people at IBM, as one of the first U.S. employees, had paid leave, insurance from the employer plus an elegant employee’s best-dressed uniform and a well-developed system.
IBM also has a long-term relationship with its customers.
From the beginning, the company was brilliant at harnessing talent – as one of the first companies in the world to abolish any discrimination, so it could choose.
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan is that Palmisana will replace IBM next year with a woman – Virginia Rometty.
IBM has been in business for 30 years, and is still the leader in sales, marketing and strategy.
In recent years, IBM has been doing so-called “online brainstormings,” from which many future strategies and innovations emerge.
No wonder there are enough ideas - almost half a million people work in the company.
Institutions with a good name
A firm position in the business ensures the company’s strong internal and external image.
“In the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than just a technology company,” said Professor of Economics at Harvard Business School and author of the book on IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
“IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems by using technology,” said George Colony of Forrester Research.
As the company itself says, the difference between entering the market and creating a market evenly.
IBM – or “Big Blue” as it is known for its logo in the United States – has grown into one of the world’s largest companies in a hundred years.
It is arguably the most versatile technology company – developing hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services across a range of products from servers to nanotechnology.
She holds the most patents from all of America’s technology companies, and five of her employees have won the Nobel Prize.
Her inventions include an ATM, a debit card, a financial swap, a bar code or a disk.
IBM, with about $220 billion this year, became the second-largest technology company by market capitalization (the first being Apple), when it first surpassed Microsoft since 1996.
A Look Forward
Not all products and innovations have hit the taste of customers and times - IBM, for example, has failed to bet on its own OS/2 operating system, Prodigy online services or IBM PCjr computers.
“If your business is built on moving forward, you can’t emotionally cling to the past,” says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its foundations on many platforms – and if they don’t work, then leave them.
Unlike, for example, the competitor Microsoft, which basically stands and falls on the Windows operating system.
Perspective technology
IBM’s market share of services is highest, with about one-fifth of them being software and hardware.
In 1990, he was the strongest representative of hardware with more than half of the shares.
Since 2000, IBM has sold low-performing assets worth $15 billion, while at the same time investing $58 billion in the purchase of prospective technologies.
Investment has been going on since 2008, when the world’s modern-day financial crisis was overrun for the first time.
IBM is acting according to a reference to its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who also increased the volume of investments during the Great Depression.
So far, it seems that IBM is going through the current crisis unaffected.
IBM’s share price has risen by 120 percent since the beginning of 2008, with the company’s net profit continuously rising.
IBM’s corporate motto is to change everything, but not its values.
Therefore, it can be expected that even if another crisis comes, this flexible giant will manage it.
IBM's History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded a hundred years ago in New York City and was originally called the Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM took over only in 1924 - it was originally a brand used for the company's branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later IBM merged four companies whose history goes back to the eighties of the nineteenth century.
They owned technologies such as the famous "switches," i.e. clocks recording the employee's arrival and departure.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired the company’s Supervisory Board.
Flint hired Thomas J. Watson, head of the rival company, to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founders of IBM – Watson’s thoughts are still built on the invincible corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began manufacturing and selling all kinds of machines for business – from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years Watson has managed the company, it doubled its turnover to $9 million and began a massive expansion of the company to all parts of the world.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after nearly forty years in the boss’s chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence, developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, people and computers from IBM helped NASA fly into space - to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the famous man's flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers – the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "pécéchique," which was established by the computer standard of the time, called the IBM 5150, was released in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold computer manufacturing to Chinese company Lenovo, bought the consulting part of PricewaterhouseCoopers, and began to devote itself fully to consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has paid off in the last three years is the concept of Smarter Planet, the “smarter planet.”
Its aim is to make smart use of technologies in unplanned areas so far, and to improve the situation, for example, in transport or urban management.
For the commerce sector, IBM has recently introduced the "Smart Commerce" platform, which helps traders manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in India.
It established its branch in then Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM, the Czech Republic also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Centre for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also a world-class research team dealing with voice recognition.
