How tour prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in what was then Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time sold in the vast majority only trips to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists thus traveled on holiday to the sea to the DDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimea near the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
The light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned towards the West and the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia was subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely individually even within the socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed a calling letter from that country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to stand on the front overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" in the travel agency.
However, it was not even won.
The so-called foreign exchange pledge, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to “politically unreliable people” who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign exchange pledge it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for the trip to the West.
By far the most common, however, the Czechs spent their holidays in the country, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs acquired and this habit survives to this day.
Thus, the travel of the Czechs experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While by 1989 vacation in the DDR or Bulgaria was our maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations abroad in countries all over the world.
The huge paradox, which we are no longer aware of today, is that it was not possible to travel freely to the most popular Croatia for us at the moment until 1989, as it was part of then Yugoslavia.
At the end of the 1990s, the visa requirement for neighbouring Western European countries was lifted, which triggered a huge wave of short-term visits to Austria, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look there for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, the Czechs’ trips to the parks in the tents fell asleep, as our incomes at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of Czech travel at this time was driving your own food, cans, salads, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely exchangeable Czech krona, so that our tourists could finally buy Western currency freely for many decades.
However, our standard of living and, as a result, average wages have increased, leading to another important moment around 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started to regularly prepare flights by charter air connections since 1997, which has reduced air travel by means of the possibility of contracting quantitative discounts compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had already had visa-free contacts to virtually all developed countries of the world, except the USA, which further facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution travel occurred in 2000, when, thanks to considerable demand, the first direct charter flight to exotica was taken from the Czech Republic, it was to Thailand.
From this year onwards, Czech tourists fly direct charters to warm faraway countries every year, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by around 100,000 Czechs each year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States revoked the visa for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in history, the Czechs spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent on one foreign holiday including the cost of accommodation more than CZK 15 thousand per person.
