An emotionally powerful new book by Peter Englund titled Beauty and the Sorrow (The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War) begins with such a long list of protagonists as your head spins.
One tip on how to keep up at the moment: Carefully scrape this page and make a bookmark out of it.
You will get to know all the people very well in Mr. Englund's novel, and this list will serve as a navigation - like a beacon - at times when, like men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also a new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite correctly, as an "antihistorical work".
It contains several very well-known names, important contracts or famous battles, on the contrary, it lacks almost ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates on tactics and equipment.
It's not even a book about what happened, the author explains, but rather a "book about what it was like". It's mainly about "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and Sadness" combines the war experiences of 20 more or less dozen men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, rescue drivers and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go crazy, or die.
Their lives fade like flames of candles lit in the church - new ones are added to the web of destinies, while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book is different from the classic historical novels.
It alters the notion that the First World War was only about terrible funeral battles on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sadness" also explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve problems with the fact that bee nests fall on them, have to spend Christmas in the shadow of the pyramids or face the presence of tse-tse fly.
From the very beginning, it was a very touching reading.
War will devour people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling gunpowder.
When the shooting starts in the distance and you are the woman who is at home with your children, will you run away or stay?
Who's actually getting closer?
Almost no one understands what is happening, not even why the whole war was started.
"The vacuum created by the lack of facts," Mr. Englund remarked, "was filled with riddles, assumptions, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
"Beauty and Sadness" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are taken entirely from biographies, letters and other materials already published. . . .
The descriptions of their lives may sound terrifying and compelling, but thanks to the incorporation of tiny moments and details they are absolutely alive and credible.
Many of them talk about spending and dealing with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says: "Insignias, everywhere the same substitutes."
"Coffee stamp, imitation of aluminum, imitation of rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
It goes even further and describes the food substitutes in Germany.
It mentions "meat made of pressed rice cooked in scooped fat (and supplemented with a false bone of wood), tobacco from dried roots and dried potato shells, boots with wooden soles".
There were “837 registered substitutes for meat in the production of steams and 511 registered substitutes for coffee”.
Some stories are about honor and courage.
One American finds within himself an inner cradle of savagery and brutality, and declares of war: "Finally you will understand that this is human nature, not to sit in comfortable chairs with cigarettes and whiskeys."
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he is most likely to die soon and no one will even notice it, let alone to grieve.
“When one finally settles for sacrifice, one would at least expect it to happen in front of the eyes of a grateful audience,” he writes.
Instead, he feels like a "convict who he secretly hangs."
Other remarks relate to the departure of the old Europe and the emergence of new horrors.
“Conflict has increasingly become an economic competition and a competitive struggle,” writes Mr Englund, “a war between factories.”
He captured what he calls "a new kind of beast of the coming century: an expressive and ideologically admirable mass murderer in tailor-made clothes, who performs his bloodshed without getting up from the table."
People behave completely unexpectedly, subjugation alternates with heroism.
Mr. Englund also describes soldiers who deliberately tried to catch some sexual illness from prostitutes in order to avoid serving on the front.
"The greatest example of this behavior was the trade in gonococcus puss, which soldiers bought and tortured their genitals in the hope of ending up in the hospital," he writes.
"The most desperate ones even wiped it in their eyes, which often blinded them for the rest of their lives."
In this translation from the Swedish by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund's prose is frizzy, but not in any way obvious, which fits perfectly with his human theme.
In dozens of small outputs, it captures the way in which the war “dissolved completely uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred”.
People are starting to wonder why their leaders are forced to fight.
The best books about the First World War mostly rather than with a comprehensive narrative worked with clues, such as "World War I and Modern Memories" by Paul Fussell or novels such as "On the Western Front Peace" by Erich Maria Remarque.
Mr. Englund prefers an unconventional notion.
His book has the most overwhelming endings that have no period in popular scholarly literature.
