After this summer’s tragedy, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just go to Facebook.
“We realized that getting them isn’t really that hard at all,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the UK’s research team on European digital populism.
The stock of personal information on Facebook is so vast, says Bartlett, that scientists have had enough to simply use ads on the site and thus accurately identify the search demographic — something marketing staff have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe, paying attention to them and sending them advertisements, but instead of inviting them to their own groups through them, they invited them to their own groups or offered them to their own groups, they invited them to their dietary products.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans from 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries – without having to leave the office at all.
“It’s a whole new way of doing research,” Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not that surprising: online right-wing groups are all-young men who are pounding the rising rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, “those who combine their online activism with offline activism are smarter, more democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen.”
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and political researchers use this site to study everything from health issues to social trends that hide behind state updates, wall posts, and the "Like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. On average, each of them will provide three different data per day, making this social network literally an “information supernova” that is behind the development of many new research studies. The number of academic papers in which Facebook has become a name has increased by 80 percent.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the opportunity to study people without having to bother them somewhere on the street.
“It used to be that when you wanted to conduct a survey of people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“You’d have to get to the side where you’d never be let go,” says Bartlett.
“Facebook is breaking all of this down – you’re just going straight to them.”
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify a socio-health problem and avoid them.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Morenova of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who discussed their drinking outcomes on Facebook were much more at risk of the problem of alcoholism than students who were silent on the topic.
Morenov<0xC3><0xA1> suggests that peers of students monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who publishes too many drunken statuses.
"The problem can't be solved unless you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of the paper, Dr. Morena and director of the Center for Children's Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle.
“We’ve found a way to identify endangered children that we wouldn’t otherwise have a chance to discover.”
Facebook is constantly surveying the data of its users.
The information team of the website developed statistics on the relationship status and Valentine's Day relationship, the participation in the elections in 2010 and the satisfaction coefficient of the nation (mainly using the information to which they had access to the information - the access to information after the internet freedom was obtained).
But Facebook users know that the page is being watched, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the option to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the page needs to provide their personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don’t even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect data offline, but online data is accessible to everyone.
“I don’t think most of the users even thought that scientists could look at their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted using his students’ public Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, they took it so that the information was only between them and their friends."
It is then also necessary to consider the question of methodology.
Even when researching offline there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
It is not possible to verify on Facebook how much information on the profile and posts on the wall are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn explains.
That’s why Selwin, who has spent many years researching new technologies, believes that pencils and notebooks remain the best possible tool to use in research.
“When you go into the real world and talk to real people, it’s something that can’t be replaced,” he says.
“Social research should be about society and social activities – and a lot of social activities are still going on offline,” he said.
