How to Recognize a Lie
A fleeting look at recent newspaper headlines tells how serious and ubiquitous lies and deceptions are in everyday life.
Republican presidential nominee Herman Cain has a full-time job accusing him of sexually harassed several women — both sides say the other is lying.
Managers at Penn State University were accused of misconduct when they tried to hide records of a retired football coach sexually assaulting a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught telling U.S. President Barack Obama with a microphone that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
The lie has been able to destroy entire careers and undermine the stability of many countries.
New York Congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by publishing information that was immediately refuted by undeniable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was accused of abusing finances from his campaign to try to hide his non-marriage.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that rallied around Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinska.
It's all about cheating at school and at the university.
There are cases when teachers give their students test answers themselves, just to make them look good in their judgements.
Mentors who should teach the opposite are sending out a message that lies and fraud are acceptable.
How many frauds do we face?
Studies show that in a single day you lie somewhere between 10 and 200 cases.
Let’s assume that many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers bludgeoned three times in their lives during the first ten minutes of the first meeting.
Determining lies, or “recognizing lies,” is a necessary skill that everyone should acquire, whether for personal or professional reasons.
However, it is not a social game that would be similar, let's say, to the <0xC5><0xA0>ar<0xC3><0xA1>da, when one shouts, "I have you." The recognition of deception is a serious branch of science working with the scientific data of the philosophies collected by the philosophies of the sub-projects collected during the past six decades.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lies have been refuted.
The liars look you in the eye.
It's not like they're sniffing, sniffing, blushing, or embroidering.
Of course, do not deduce from the fact that it is somehow difficult for liars to notice and uncover.
A trained lie identifier can reveal the truth from the sentence structure, the small expressions on the face, the way questions are formed and their timing.
I have spent several years collecting scientific knowledge from a vast and developing field of the recognition of lies, and it is clear that the discovery of lies is a modern skill, which can be easily learned after your work, and can be useful to you in today's complex world.
Good liars are able to read well in others, let them sink into alertness, direct their emotions, and intuitively realize how the other party accepts them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men carry more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more lies "focused on others" - usually to protect one's feelings - that married people lie less often than their partners.
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know someone is lying?
First, look at the normal behavior of the subject.
It's called "initial observation."
Thanks to it, he will have a later finding of what to compare with.
Notice the holding of the body of the subject, his laughter, working with the voice.
You should know if someone is constantly kicking their feet so that you don’t falsely accuse them of lying just because they start kicking their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then try to determine the sums of false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
However, consider it only as a warning sign, not as a proof of a lie.
People carrying a lie can stop moving the upper half of the body when they try to remember their fictional story, they can turn the tip of the boots to the door, lean towards the east, change the posture of the body significantly, or expose them to a "slip-off" after the interview.
People conducting interviews often give a false signal that the interview is at the end, just to see what relief will look like after it’s finished.
Also understand the subject’s language.
Famous is the story of how Scott Peterson once spoke and used the past time when he claimed his murdered wife was alive, which sparked a nationwide search for her body.
The fraudulent individuals can also express themselves in an apt way: “I had no sexual relationship with that lady... Miss Lewinska” or they repeat the difficult question in its entirety.
The most common verbal characters are only very minor.
Someone can use a lot of "smoothing language" when answering a difficult question, "Well... to tell the truth... from what I know... from my best mind."
In such an answer, we do not know too many facts and often it is another warning signal.
There is no magic to reveal every lie, but it is possible to acquire the skills by which a lie can be traced.
With the help of these skills, a person will have a greater chance of not encountering a liar and a fraudster in his personal and professional life.
