As a result, the appeal filed by the Senate was rejected because a qualified majority of eight votes was not obtained, which was necessary for the court to express the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the said decree, which thus remains valid.
The draft judgment drawn up by Minister Olga S<0xC3><0xA1>nchez Cordero proposes the possibility to declare the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of all issues relating to radio and television is a matter that is reserved according to the law to the Federal Commission for Telecommunications (Cofetel).
Only Zald<0xC3><0xAD>var, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and S<0xC3><0xA1>nchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies supported the constitutional dispute in an effort to combat the decree. Minister S<0xC3><0xA1>nchez Cordero accepted the demands and suspended the application of the decree and all actions described in it, leading to the transition to digitalization.
The Ministers’ meeting also decided to reject the complaint submitted by the Chamber of Deputies without engaging in a discussion on the proposal, which is also in charge of Minister S<0xC3><0xA1>nchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not identify himself with the arguments of the proposal in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general standards measures for the preparation of public administration.
“I don’t think that even if it did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body,” he recalled that planning public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector belongs to the federal executive, who has a constitutional mandate to determine the direction of the state.
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the biggest changes the world has experienced in recent years. It is related to better use of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
It believes that deferring change would defer the benefits of digitalisation, which requires decisions in the public interest, because digitalisation does not only have a technical dimension, but also "affects economic, social, political and national security issues".
As he stressed, these issues "require the operation of the entire system, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the state. It includes a whole range of competences that the Constitution entrusts to the government of the state".
He recalled that a number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to the digital system and have done so through their governments, even though they had highly specialized technical bodies at their disposal.
He said it was not possible for the government to introduce into the administrative area compliance with laws prepared by the legislature by issuing a dissenting decree, which to some extent interferes with the jurisdiction of the Congress.
