Monti said he would present to the president the results of his talks with political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were overcome.
"The frame is now well-marked," he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, i.e. in a much shorter time than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is trying to fight the political and financial crisis, which has caused the debt to rise to an unsustainable level.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Montim, must approve a tough package of austerity measures demanded by European leaders, only to restore Italy's broken credibility.
Due to the volatility of the markets, the interest rates on Italian BTP bonds with a ten-year maturity exceeded the 7% threshold, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to apply for bailouts.
