Fujimori has been hospitalized again due to medical tests.
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized in a public hospital on Tuesday, where he will be tested for muscle loss he suffers in the lower limbs, his attending physician reported.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving a 25-year sentence for human rights violations committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, which has caused him to have surgery four times and is now under the control of doctors.
MEP Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal doctor, told Canal N that Fujimori will undergo tests at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases within three days, where they should find out why he hurts and why he loses strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga said that in his opinion Fujimori could get mercy for humanitarian reasons, but the former president himself does not want mercy because he feels innocent.
He had surgery four times because of cancer of the tongue, dropped 18 kilograms and added to these problems were other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, cysts on the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been serving his sentence since September 2007 in the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by a murder squad of illegally operating troops in the first years of his government.
