Secretary Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come presented details of the plane crash in which the governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven other people died.
The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the investigation into the accident in which Secretary of State Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people died show that the helicopter hit the ground directly with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt a forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come, the secretary for Communications and Transport, said that before the plane started, the pilot noted that climatic conditions allow flights.
"The parts that appear indicate that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, the wings got entangled in a branch of trees 25 meters from the place where the unit lost the corpse."
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it met all the requirements for the transport of personnel.
In addition, it stated that, based on the investigation carried out in the area of the collision, no components were found on the ground.
"The search found that parts of the aircraft were not located elsewhere, so the aircraft ran into the mainland as a whole.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, met all the requirements for the transportation of people.
The terrain exhibits a slope with a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that at the moment it is most important to get the results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation can take several months or up to one year.
Gilberto L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the collision, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was moving at travel speed and there was an accident on soft ascent terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that at the time of the accident it was a common overflight operation," he said.
At the press conference, SCT representative Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come named six key investigative points:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aeronautical standards, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, that is, the crew must see on the ground during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports in the AICM indicate adequate start conditions, in accordance with which the aircraft is proceeding towards the border, between the DF and the State of Mexico there were visible layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is likely that because of the cloudy crew they were looking for a lower area and greater visibility all the way to the Cuernavaca valley.
Location of the collision.
Coordinates of the collision and the last recording of the helicopter from the radar coincide, it is likely that before the collision there was no loss of control or disruption of the flight trajectory.
Dispersion of the remnants of the aircraft in a restricted territory:
The information we currently have at our disposal allows us to assume that the collision occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
The pattern of the dispersal of the aircraft's remains indicates that the helicopter was intact at the time of the impact on the mainland.
There was no fire or explosion.
There was no evidence at the scene of the accident that would indicate an explosion or a fire had occurred.
The latest results of the investigation show that several contacts with the mainland may have occurred.
During the field work, the remains of the aircraft were found at an altitude of up to 9,200 feet above sea level, the terrain is tilted, the slope goes from seven to 30 degrees.
The photographs show the footage where there is likely to be a breakdown along the mentioned route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter could have come into contact with the ground in several places.
After a careful search in the vicinity of the accident, no helicopter remains were found in an area larger than the landing site, which reinforces the presumption that the collision occurred in a state when the helicopter was still intact.
Mexican Institute of Health Insurance Launches Gene Research That Causes Obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research in order to discover the gene responsible for obesity in children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the Institute of IPN
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to discover a gene that causes obesity in children and adolescents. The research called "The Genetics of Obesity in Children and Adolescents" will allow you to get results related to obesity.
In a report, Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry from the Specialized Hospital of the National Health Center of the 21st Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was set up.
This team relies on the support of specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
Participation in the research can also be made by the general public, with or without permission. People can come to the IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where they will take youth tests from 8 a.m. each meeting.
He stressed that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Center (Mexico State) and as of October 8, this activity is also carried out at the Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt Sports Center (Eastern Mexico State).
Once data are obtained from 500 to 600 children, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to determine the components and significance of genetics in relation to the development of obesity, and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on November 14, he recalled that the goal is to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on age.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He clarified that every Saturday all participants were subjected to anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure was measured, glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin levels were determined and the genes were examined (trying to identify genes).
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez said the research reflects health care workers’ concerns about the alarming increase in child weight.
"Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years there was a 77% increase in obesity in boys and 47% in girls, and a dramatic increase in overweight," the IMSS expert said.
He noted that one of the reasons for the search for indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from other populations in their genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% of Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in the genes that are responsible for the development of diabetes and obesity.
He explained that in general the genetics of obesity is commonly explained as the inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calorie) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they are given an overall assessment of the condition of the children, which determines whether they have any known overweight or obesity.
He said that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-diabetic conditions.
The information is confidential so far, doctors pass it on in writing to parents and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes that they need to make in order to prevent their children from getting sick.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle that means a lack of daily physical activity, full-day sitting in front of the TV and using the means of transport instead of walking for a short walk.
Overweight also causes a large calorie intake, that is, greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no asphalt in UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalts with polymers, creating a mixture that has better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature.
If the tile lining was properly taken care of, the lining of the lining would not need to be repaired almost 200,000 linings after each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, Rafael Herrer N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, a scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) would have warned the lining of the lining.
In his lecture, the Technological Cause of Explosives, which he spoke in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, which should produce a mixture of asphalts having similar characteristics to asphalts, but at the same time dissipate the asphalts.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with an extremely warm climate, for example in some cities in the north of the country, thus improving functionality and reducing the formation of excavations.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of the oil, is a group of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a large molecular weight called asphalts, and others with a low molecular weight called maltenes.
The viscoelastic character of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees has a high viscosity, and at 50 degrees is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day depending on the weather conditions and temperature, the chemical engineering expert warned.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible tile, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the topmost layers is an asphalt insert, formed by small stones embedded in the asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that makes up the insert is filled with asphalt.
When passing cars or creating pressure, it is thus possible for the forces in the tiles to disperse well.
If it were modified asphalt, they would disperse even better, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that on the asphalt insert is placed the last layer called the coat, made of fine stone, that is, sand also poured into the asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with the rims of vehicles, it must have a greater mechanical force than the asphalt insert and must ensure friction of the track.
Since as part of the tile will be exposed to a large load, the coat must be sufficiently thick and pay attention to the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. In particular, water has a big impact on the functionality of asphalt inserts.
Once the terrain is damp, the water spreads inwards and is difficult to get out, this causes softening of all layers of the tile and thus the formation of cracks.
He explained that during the creation of the extrusions, the first film of the coat is damaged and only after that the asphalt insert is damaged. However, the damage does not occur at one point, but it is a slow process that should stop already at the first signs using suitable maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the creation of bulges, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of the tile must correspond to the load of the vehicles and must ensure that this load does not exceed the load.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that when it comes to asphalt, we still have a lot of work to do and research is in the beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and make it easy to repair the outflows without having to use them.
