Nord Stream, the new entry port of Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream long-distance pipeline connecting Eastern Europe directly to Russia and led along the bottom of the Baltic Sea began to operate.
It has to supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part in the inauguration of Nord Stream, a new pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly underwater.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned the valve controlling the Russian gas inlet into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will flow into Western Europe each year through the first 1,224 km long pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Mecklenburg-Pomeranian Commonwealth.
The second pipeline, to be completed by the end of 2012, will allow a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas to be supplied, which is equivalent to the entire French consumption.
And it is already recalled the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge building has the character of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries protested strongly against the project.
Nord Stream will in fact allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany without being transported to the country by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing some power: the possibility of pushing Russia with threats of shutting down access to Western European markets becomes more difficult for them.
This was most strongly expressed by Warsaw when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet Pact", with a reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means saying that this is a politically sensitive topic.
Western Europe, with its support for this Russian project, has gained greater confidence in its purchases.
But this is at the cost of weakening Europe’s energy, because the project has created gaps between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Just five years ago, Russia was able to pursue its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy, high-gas-consuming Western states whose bearings are nearing their end.
“This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that connects us organically,” Fillon said at the opening ceremony of the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom’s leaders, who are present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply site.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a significant technical act.
The submarine pipe is made of steel equipped with a concrete shell to protect it from the anchorages of seagoing vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, minefields dating back to the Second World War had to be avoided.
“For their safety, almost a hundred had to be removed or destroyed,” said Jens Müller, a spokesperson for Nord Stream.
Measures for the protection of fauna and flora had also to be stepped up.
The pipe itself is a long metal hose weighing like 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted anywhere in its entire length by either valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was supposed to be built near Sweden, but the project leader rejected it when the Swedes were only reluctant to see the Russian state company as it was permanently settling off their coast.
“In the event of a failure, we will stop the gas passage in less than 1 minute,” explains Jens Müller.
In the event of a gas leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, since the welds were designed to create a gap once every 100,000 years.
The gas pipeline’s condition is checked from the outside by an underwater robot pulled by the ship, while the gas pipeline’s interior is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is inserted into the inside of the pipe and is compressed by gas.
It will provide accurate information on possible deformations of metal parts during the three-day journey at 3 m/s.
The long-distance pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without requiring the slightest repair.
The circulation of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the target.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leading position remains Gazprom, which holds a 51% stake.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased to this company a five-year contract that could be renewed, all its gas transport capacity.
“Gazprom will have a profit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported,” explains Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work is expected to reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez Group, the investment costs amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will come back to them, because only Gazprom takes the risk.
Gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
The 4.5-metre-high valves form the gas outlet gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
When full capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
